<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1947-03-11T17:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1947-03-11T17:00:00-05:00" n="439" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d439">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 Council/3–1147: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Brazil</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Pawley</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                            </seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Rio de Janeiro</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1947-03-11T19:00:00-03:00">March 11,
                                    1947—7 p.m.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>288. London’s telegram 1154, February 20. Embassy is not aware of any
                            undertaking “to make satisfactory arrangements with Brazil in the matter
                            of reparations outside the scope of the Paris Act”.</p>
                        <p>This Embassy will be interested in learning if any conversations this
                            regard were carried on either Washington or London.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Pawley</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>